   {:e #blake3 "e4a8e72e8aaaef15d3a4d0a1bf506ff0cd19bd8eb25aeffafc471dbe7e849643" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Consistency engine implements 5-tier contradiction detection (APP-ADR-038): Tier 2 = Graph (typed edges, governance overlap, cycles), Tier 3 = SAT (semi-formal to propositional encoding via gophersat), Tier 4 = Heuristic (polarity inversion, quantifier conflict, numeric bounds, LSI), Tier 5 = SMT (semi-formal to SMT-LIB2 via Z3 subprocess), Tier 6 = LLM-as-judge (semantic tension via Anthropic API). Conflict types: governance_overlap, neg_spec_violation, polarity_inversion, quantifier_conflict, numeric_bound_conflict, circular_implication, sat_unsatisfiable, smt_unsatisfiable, semantic_tension. Zero false positives invariant (APP-INV-019). Max tier configurable.; APP-INV-010 (Oplog Append-Only): ALIGNED - Append() uses os.O_APPEND|os.O_CREATE|os.O_WRONLY flags. No DELETE/UPDATE operations exist in oplog package. ReadAll/ReadFiltered are read-only. JSONL format with monotonic timestamps (time.Now().UTC()). The only mutation path is filesystem-level (outside code control), which is expected.; Session entity: :task/t-1e52990a; LLM integration has two layers: (1) llm/provider.go — Provider interface with graceful degradation (Available() gates features), uses Anthropic Claude Haiku via Messages API, centralized confidence constants (unanimous=0.95, majority=0.80 for 3-vote evaluation). (2) autoprompt — the state monad: every command returns (output, state, guidance) triple. State tracks 5 confidence dimensions [coverage, depth, coherence, completeness, formality] each 0-10, plus active_thread, limiting_factor, spec_drift. Guidance provides observed_mode, DoF_hint (degrees of freedom), suggested_next, attenuation. Budget decays: k*=12 at depth 0, decrement by 1 every 5 invocations, floor=3. Token target: 2000 at k*=12, 300 at k*=3. THIS IS THE PRECURSOR TO BRAID'S GUIDANCE SYSTEM.; Bilateral cycle has 4 phases: (1) DISCOVER: record discovery events to JSONL (thread-based, sequenced), classify findings, build context. (2) REFINE: select focus dimension with lowest confidence (priority: completeness>coherence>depth>coverage>formality), surface ambiguities by detecting invariant pairs with opposing keywords (must/must-not, always/never). (3) DRIFT: measure spec-impl divergence across 3 types (unspecified, unimplemented, contradictions) with quality breakdown (correctness, depth, coherence) plus process drift metrics. (4) ABSORB: bidirectional reconciliation using keyword overlap scoring (match_threshold=0.6, reverse=0.4) producing correspondences, undocumented_behavior, unimplemented_spec.; Go CLI has 38 internal packages: absorb, annotate, autoprompt, bundle, cascade, causal, challenge, checklist, cli, consistency, coverage, diff, discover, discovery, drift, events, exemplar, impact, implorder, llm, materialize, oplog, parser, process, progress, projector, query, refine, renderer, search, skeleton, state, storage, triage, validator, witness, workspace. This is the full package inventory for architecture mapping.; Session entity: :task/t-f9e173ca; Materialize engine implements deterministic fold: events are causally sorted via Kahn's algorithm (APP-INV-074), then replayed into SQLite materialized state. Key invariants: fold determinism (APP-INV-073), materialization idempotency (APP-INV-075), log canonicality (APP-INV-071). Three built-in stream processors fire as post-fold observers: (1) ValidationProcessor checks structural completeness of crystallized INVs/ADRs/modules, (2) ConsistencyProcessor notes cross-refs for deferred verification, (3) DriftProcessor marks when drift check needed after content change. Derived events carry causes[] provenance chain. This is the CQRS write side — events in, materialized SQL state out.; APP-INV-019 (Contradiction Graph Soundness): DIVERGENT - The invariant states 'False positives are not acceptable at any tier' but Tier 4 (heuristic) reports contradictions at confidence 0.5-0.7 with explicit resolution hints saying 'this may be a false positive' and 'verify these address the same subject.' Polarity inversion detection uses regex matching ('must X' vs 'must not X') which inherently cannot verify subject overlap. This is a known architectural tension: heuristic tiers trade precision for recall. The dedup function keeps highest-confidence per pair but does not filter out low-confidence results.; Storage layer uses 30-table normalized SQLite schema (APP-ADR-005). Core entity types: SpecIndex, SourceFile, Section (heading tree), Invariant (6-component INV blocks), ADR (with options), NegativeSpec, QualityGate, VerificationPrompt/Check, MetaInstruction, WorkedExample, WhyNotAnnotation, ComparisonBlock, PerformanceBudget/Entry, StateMachine/Cell, GlossaryEntry, CrossReference, Module/Relationship, Manifest, InvariantRegistry, InvariantWitness, ChallengeResult, Transaction/TxOperation, FormattingHint. This is a relational model — contrasts with braid's datom model.; Cascade package (cascade/cascade.go) zero tests, same error suppression as context.go: lines 74, 84, 94, 127, 139 all use blank identifiers for storage errors. Additionally line 48 reveals dead code: depth parameter is validated (lines 42-47) but then immediately discarded with '_ = depth // reserved for future multi-hop cascade'. The depth parameter flows through the Options struct from user input but has NO EFFECT. The CLI exposes --depth but it does nothing — this is a user-facing lie. FINAL SYNTHESIS: The codebase has three systemic quality issues: (1) Error suppression via blank identifiers — found in storage/db.go, search/context.go, cascade/cascade.go, annotate/scan.go, drift/drift.go, witness/eval.go. (2) 12/38 packages untested, including critical infrastructure. (3) Dead code patterns — unused depth parameter, reinvented stdlib functions.; Concurrency analysis: Go CLI is entirely single-threaded. Zero goroutines, zero mutexes, zero channels across all 38 internal packages. Global mutable state found: parser/diagnostic.go line 54 uses a package-level var GlobalDiagnostics with no synchronization. Comment claims 'safe for single-threaded use' but this is a global mutable singleton — any future concurrency addition would silently race. Also, the comment on line 25-26 is misleading: it says 'safe to append concurrently' but only because extractors are sequential.; APP-INV-015 (Deterministic Hashing): ALIGNED - sha256Hex() is a 3-line function: sha256.Sum256([]byte(s)) formatted as hex. No salt, no timestamp, no process ID, no nonce. Used for content_hash on sections, source files, invariants, and ADRs. Produces identical output for identical input across all platforms per Go's crypto/sha256.; APP-INV-001 (Round-Trip Fidelity): ALIGNED - RenderMonolith writes stored raw_text verbatim back to disk (atomic rename). ParseDocument stores raw text on ingest. Trivially correct by construction: raw_text in = raw_text out. 5 test functions in roundtrip_test.go cover monolith, modular, CLI self-spec, idempotency, and line preservation.; Oplog package (oplog/oplog.go) has zero tests despite being critical infrastructure: it manages the append-only event log (APP-INV-020) and is the backbone of event sourcing (APP-ADR-007, APP-ADR-015). The ReadFiltered function has a subtle issue: line 111 silently skips records with unparseable timestamps (error from time.Parse is caught but record is still skipped without logging). If a record has a malformed timestamp, filtering by --since will silently drop it. Also: 10MB max line buffer at line 89 is arbitrary and could silently truncate long records. Both the skeleton package (zero tests) and oplog package (zero tests) have well-structured code but ZERO verification.; Session entity: :session/s-1774400978; Systematic error suppression pattern in search/context.go: 12+ instances of storage.List* calls with error return silently discarded via blank identifier. Examples: line 221 invs, _ := storage.ListInvariants; line 260 gates, _ := storage.ListQualityGates; line 273 negSpecs, _ := storage.ListNegativeSpecs; line 357 glossaryTerms, _; line 464/476/504/517/529/542 all same pattern. Also drift/drift.go line 345-346 does identical err suppression. This is a codebase-wide anti-pattern: functions that query the database suppress errors to avoid cluttering the happy path, but mask real failures like corrupted DB or missing tables.; SQL safety in storage/insert.go is GOOD: all 25+ Insert functions use parameterized queries (?-placeholders). No raw string interpolation in SQL values. However, deleteSpecData line 749 uses fmt.Sprintf to build table names — safe since table names are hardcoded strings, but violates the principle of least surprise. One SQL injection vector: if the tables list were ever populated from user input, this would be exploitable.; Query package (query/query.go) has zero tests but contains critical logic: regex-based target parsing for sections/invariants/ADRs/gates, fragment assembly from DB, cross-reference resolution, backlink fetching. The parseTarget function uses 4 different regex patterns and a string-prefix fallback. Without tests, regressions in target parsing would silently break the entire context bundle system (search/context.go depends on query.QueryTarget). The fetchRefTargetText function silently returns empty string on DB errors — connects to the error suppression pattern observed earlier.; CLI has 47 Cobra commands organized in 5 groups. CORE (7): next, parse, validate, coverage, drift, spec, issue, triage, materialize, project. INVESTIGATION (8): context, search, query, exemplar, impact, cascade, contradict, history, bisect, blame. IMPROVEMENT (6): refine, discover, absorb, witness, scan, challenge. PLANNING (7): progress, implorder, checklist, bundle, skeleton, diff, tasks. UTILITY (12): render, seed, log, tx, state, checkpoint, init, patch, manifest, agenthelp, version, rename, import, replay, snapshot. Bare 'ddis' delegates to 'next' which shows current status and recommended action. Global flags: -q (suppress guidance), --db (explicit DB path).; Go CLI architecture synthesis: 37,991 LOC production code + 12,467 LOC tests = 50,458 LOC in internal packages alone. Architecture follows CQRS pattern: WRITE side (events -> materialize -> fold -> SQLite state), READ side (storage queries -> renderer). Cross-cutting: autoprompt state monad (output, state, guidance) threads through all commands. 5-tier consistency engine for contradiction detection. Bilateral cycle (discover -> refine -> drift -> absorb) is the primary workflow loop. The annotate package bridges code->spec via ddis:implements/maintains/maintains annotations in source code. Key architectural insight: the Go CLI conflates kernel and application — storage schema hardcodes INV/ADR/NEG types, autoprompt hardcodes 5 DDIS confidence dimensions. This is exactly what braid's C8 (substrate independence) aims to decouple.; APP-INV-006 (Transaction State Machine): ALIGNED - Enforced at two levels: (1) SQL CHECK constraint allows only 'pending', 'committed', 'rolled_back' states, (2) CommitTransaction and RollbackTransaction both use WHERE status='pending', preventing transitions from committed or rolled_back. CreateTransaction always sets initial status to 'pending'. The invariant's three allowed transitions (pending->committed, pending->rolled_back, nothing else) are correctly implemented.; Error handling gap in storage/db.go: Lines 71-73 and 106 call db.Exec() without checking errors (fire-and-forget pattern). Migration steps silently fail — data loss risk if INSERT INTO invariant_witnesses or DROP TABLE fails. Also lines 125-126, 134. Pattern: migration code consistently ignores Exec return values.; Test coverage gaps: 12 of 38 internal packages (31%) have ZERO test files: bundle, cascade, diff, exemplar, impact, implorder, oplog, progress, query, renderer, skeleton, state. Several of these are critical: oplog (event logging), query (the query engine), state (session state management), impact (impact analysis). The query package is especially concerning — it handles all spec element lookups and cross-reference resolution, yet has no tests. State manages session persistence with raw SQL but no test coverage.; Session entity: :task/t-606d5679; LLM provider pattern is well-structured: clean interface, graceful degradation via Available(), dependency injection for tests. However two issues: (1) The HTTP client at llm/provider.go:55 uses a 60s timeout but creates the client once in NewProvider — if the binary runs as a long-lived process, the single http.Client never refreshes DNS. (2) witness/eval.go line 125 uses json.Marshal with blank identifier (evidenceJSON, _ := json.Marshal) — if marshaling fails, it inserts an empty evidence string into the witness table, silently corrupting the audit trail. The eval package also reinvents strings.ToLower and strings.TrimSpace manually (lines 173-220).; Session entity: :task/t-cca13ee4; APP-INV-021 (Consistency Encoding Fidelity): PARTIAL - Global VarMap correctly ensures same predicates share variable IDs across invariants (preventing the violation scenario of same-name collision). However, ParseSemiFormal strips quantifiers (FOR ALL/EXISTS treated as flat propositional assertions), which is a lossy encoding that can produce false UNSAT results when two invariants quantify over different domains. The SAT tier reports at confidence 0.85 with 'verify encoding' hints. The GLOBAL namespace (APP-INV-021's requirement) is satisfied. The fidelity claim is approximately satisfied with known limitations.; APP-INV-013 (Impact Termination): DIVERGENT - The cascade.Analyze function does NOT perform BFS traversal. The depth parameter (1-5) is accepted but unused (_ = depth, line 48: 'reserved for future multi-hop cascade'). It only does direct module relationship lookups and backlink counts. Since there is no graph traversal, the cycle-safety property is trivially satisfied, but the actual invariant requirement (BFS visiting each node at most once) is vacuously true because there is no BFS at all. The multi-hop impact analysis described by the invariant is unimplemented.; Package dependency graph reveals layered architecture. FOUNDATION layer (no internal imports): storage, state, events, renderer, query, llm, exemplar, impact, diff. MIDDLE layer: consistency imports storage+llm (5 consistency strategies: heuristic, semantic, sat, smt, graph+llm). materialize imports events (fold/diff/snapshot event processing). cascade imports storage. witness imports storage+llm+annotate. UPPER layer: drift imports storage+consistency+state. absorb imports storage+autoprompt. refine imports storage+autoprompt+state. discover has its own event JSONL model (not using events package). The storage package is the central hub — imported by ~20 other packages.; Annotate package (annotate/scan.go) silently swallows two categories of errors: line 38 (WalkDir error handler returns nil, skipping unreadable dirs) and line 67 (scanFile error returns nil, skipping unreadable files). Both are intentional 'best-effort' patterns but neither logs the skip. Combined with the error suppression in context.go and db.go, this forms a codebase-wide pattern: defensive coding that masks real failures by treating all errors as non-fatal. The codebase has roughly 3 tiers of error handling quality: (1) Storage layer — mostly good, parameterized SQL, proper wrapping. (2) Query/context layer — systematic suppression via blank identifiers. (3) Scan/walk layer — intentional but unlogged error swallowing.; APP-INV-002 (Validation Determinism): ALIGNED - 20 checks run in fixed order via AllChecks() slice. No time.Now(), rand, or OS-dependent state in any check logic. Check 19 (VCS) depends on git but gracefully degrades. The Validate function is a pure fold over deterministic checks. Tests in validator_test.go verify check composability." :op :assert}
